**Comparing Strings in Java**

In Java, you can compare strings using either the `==` operator or the `equals()` method. However, they behave differently.

### Using the `==` Operator

The `==` operator checks if both variables point to the same object in memory. This means that if you have two string literals that are identical, `==` will return `true`. However, if you create two separate string objects with the same content, `==` will return `false`.

```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true

String s3 = new String("Hello");
String s4 = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(s3 == s4); // false
```

### Using the `equals()` Method

The `equals()` method checks if the content of two strings is identical. It returns `true` if both strings have the same characters in the same order.

```java
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(s1.equals(s2)); // true

String s3 = new String("Hello");
String s4 = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(s3.equals(s4)); // false
```

### When to Use Each

- **Use `==`** when you need to check if two string variables point to the same object in memory. This is useful when working with string pools or caching.

- **Use `equals()`** when you need to compare the content of two strings. This is the most common use case.

### Best Practice

In general, use `equals()` to compare strings. This ensures that your code is more robust and less prone to bugs.

